@stephane @vimalloc @mattupstate One of the big appeals (to me) of flask-jwt is that it is really light-weight and targeted specifically at basic token based authentication. I do a lot of work with apis that don't (and won't) support cookies, so I prefer to stick with a semi-stateless mechanism of authenticating. So, I think flask-jwt-extended has some cool features, but I probably won't use it in my projects.

I agree that it might be nice to configure a few things, such as the authentication endpoint and defining how you expect the body of the post request to that endpoint. Also, I need to figure out if I can get the endpoint in vanilla flask-jwt to play nicely with swagger since I'm using flask-restplus.

I'm not exactly eager to volunteer to be a maintainer (I have a few too many hobbies, and one of them needs to be held and fed milk all the time =]). However, I would really like to see flask-jwt remain light-weight and targeted at apis specifically while still being maintained with issues and pull-requests addressed as they arrive.

