Here is my solution:

I added a custom SchemaView like this:

```
# in views.py

from rest_framework_swagger.renderers import OpenAPIRenderer, SwaggerUIRenderer
from rest_framework.decorators import api_view, renderer_classes
from rest_framework import response, schemas
from app import urls

@api_view()
@renderer_classes([SwaggerUIRenderer, OpenAPIRenderer])
def schema_view(request):
    generator = schemas.SchemaGenerator(title='API Docs', patterns=urls.my_patterns, url='/api/v1/')
    return response.Response(generator.get_schema())
```

```
# in urls.py

from app import views

my_patterns = [
    ...
]

urlpatterns = [
    url(r'^api/v1/', include(my_patterns)),
    url(r'^docs/', views.schema_view),
]
```

Important to set authorization in settings:

```
# in settings.py

SWAGGER_SETTINGS = {
    'SECURITY_DEFINITIONS': {
        'token': {
            'type': 'apiKey',
            'name': 'AUTHORIZATION',
            'in': 'header',
        }
    },
}
```

This way I skip the custom permission in the documentation, but I have the authorization header in requests so I can work with it.

I hope it helps!!

