How about keeping both `query_raw()` and `query(..., raw=...)`? This would enable advanced users to run raw queries in a more convenient and robust manner while also making it easy to include raw query strings in normal queries. This would mean that you can achieve pretty much everything with `query()` alone and that the `count()` method's signature can be changed to match `query()`'s.

@j08lue It can be used to construct queries in a bit more convenient manner, though, I don't use it that way: https://scihub.copernicus.eu/userguide/3FullTextSearch#Simple_search_query
I personally like that construct since it allows me to store query parameters as a string in a config file or a DB, so I don't have to deal with serializing and deserializing dictionaries, for example. It's also useful for testing weird non-standard queries, as I have done in some of the previous PRs.

