I agree with the name `models`, however I'd move it to `controller/models`. If we ever re-write the controller in Go (unlikely, but possible), I'd imagine that the import package would be `github.com/deis/deis/controller/models`, so it'd be a quick change from `github.com/deis/deis/client/controller/models` to `github.com/deis/deis/controller/models`.

I would also move the controller interaction into a separate package. `controller/client` would be better for communicating with the API. As an brain dump, here's how I think it should look like:

```go
// A Client manages communication with the controller API.
type Client struct {
    // HTTP client used to communicate with the API.
    client *http.Client

    // URL used to communicate with the controller.
    URL *url.URL

    // Base URL for API requests.  Defaults to the v1 API, but can be
    // set to a new api endpoint if the user has customized their controller.
    // BaseURL should always be specified with a trailing slash.
    BaseURL *url.URL

    // User agent header used when communicating with the controller API.
    UserAgent string

    // Token is used to authenticate the request against the API.
    Token string

    // Username is the name of the user performing requests against the API.
    Username string

    // Handle to a local Deis settings file. By default this is found in
    // ~/.deis/client.json, but can be tweaked by setting $DEIS_PROFILE.
    // It is used to persist client data on the local machine.
    SettingsFile *os.File
}
```

This way if users require a proxy (Go handles this by default), they can extend the HTTP client to their liking by setting up their own http.Transport in the client.

I'm not sure how the API requests would be handled, but that's my 2 cents on how the controller interaction should be set up.

