@jni `random_walker` in effect finds the shortest stochastic path - with penalties paid based on some weighting function - from each point in the image back to the nearest element of each seed region. I think of it more like a graph theory problem, though it can be expressed in multiple frameworks.

The problem is that there is an inherent assumption: _*a path exists from each seed region to every point on the image*_.

We've added the ability to mask regions in this algorithm. There are good use cases for this. However, when you fence off or enclose a seed region the algorithm is going to have a problem. This is actually expected. There's no way to get to that seed!

@emmanuelle delineated our options well. We basically can either check and discard such regions or allow them to fail with a more graceful error message. I'd prefer to do the check and provide the user with an informative error message.

Below is a trivial fix that simply transposes the call to the underlying C line_aa() function if the magnitude of the slope is greater than one. It passes the above unit test. But a cleaner fix could be made by fixing the underlying C line_aa() implementation.

    # Trivial fix for scikit-image bug #1563
    def line_aa(y1, x1, y2, x2):
        dx = abs(x2-x1)
        dy = abs(y2-y1)
        if dx >= dy:
            return skimage.draw.line_aa(y1, x1, y2, x2)
        else:
            (Y, X, intensity) = skimage.draw.line_aa(x1, y1, x2, y2)
            return (X, Y, intensity)

